<refentry
  xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"
  xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"
  xmlns:svg="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
  xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
  xmlns:db="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"
  version="5.0-subset Scilab"
  xml:lang="fr"
  xml:id="lowdisc_terms">
  <info>
    <pubdate>$LastChangedDate: 18-12-2008 $</pubdate>
  </info>
  <refnamediv>
    <refname>lowdisc_terms</refname>
    <refpurpose>  Returns several terms of the sequence.</refpurpose>
  </refnamediv>
  <refsynopsisdiv>
    <title>Calling Sequence</title>
    <synopsis>[this,result] = lowdisc_terms(this,imax)</synopsis>
  </refsynopsisdiv>
  <refsection>
    <title>Parameters</title>
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>this</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>The current object.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>imax</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            The number of terms to produce in the sequence. The produced vectors have
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>result</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            The matrix containing imax terms of the sequence, from 1 up to imax. The matrix is organized as follows.
            <itemizedlist>
              <listitem>
                <para>result(1,1:dimension) is the term #1</para>
              </listitem>
              <listitem>
                <para>result(i,1:dimension) is the term #i</para>
              </listitem>
              <listitem>
                <para>result(imax,1:dimension) is the term #imax</para>
              </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </refsection>
  <refsection>
    <title>Description</title>
    <para>
      This command allows to get several elements in the sequence in one call, while
      lowdisc_next produces one element at a time.
    </para>
  </refsection>
  <refsection>
    <title>Examples</title>
    <para>
      In the following script, one uses a Halton sequence in dimension 2.
      One uses the lowdisc_terms method to produce the element from #1 to #5
      in only one call.
    </para>
    <programlisting role="example">
      rng = lowdisc_new();
      rng = lowdisc_configure(rng,"-method","halton");
      rng = lowdisc_configure(rng,"-dimension",2);
      rng = lowdisc_startup (rng);
      [rng,computed]=lowdisc_terms(rng,5);
    </programlisting>
    <para>
      The result is the following matrix, where each line is an element in the sequence.
    </para>
    <programlisting role="example">
      expected= [...
      1./4. 2./3. ;...
      3./4. 1./9. ;...
      1./8. 4./9. ;...
      5./8. 7./9. ;...
      3./8. 2./9. ];
    </programlisting>
  </refsection>
